Clipping. Recall that the squared loss of samples $(x,y)$ on point $w$ is $(x\cdot w-y)^{2}/2$ and its gradient is $ ar{(x^{}\cdot w^{}-y)x}$ . Instead of directly working with the gradient of the squared loss, we work with its clipped version. Given a clipping parameter $\kappa\,>\,0$ , the clipped gradient for a sample $(x,y)$ evaluated at point $w$ is defined as $ egin{array}{r}{
abla f(x,y,w,\kappa)\,:=\, rac{(x\cdot w-y)}{|x\cdot w-y|\vee\kappa}\kappa x}\end{array}$ = |x(·xw·w−−y|y∨)κκx. For a collection of samples S, the clipped gradient $
abla f(S,w,\kappa)$ is the average of the clipped gradients of all samples in $S$ , i.e., $ egin{array}{r}{
abla f(S,\stackrel{..}{w},\kappa):= rac{1}{|S|}\sum_{(x,y)\in S}
abla f(x,y,w,\kappa)}\end{array}$ .

